animal.description:
MACIE is an adorable mix of terrier and dachshund and more than likely a few other breeds. She is approximately 2 years of age. Macie came to RMPR from the deserts of Southern New Mexico. She was abandoned and alone after her owner died at 92 years of age. Macie was living with many other dogs at the owner's home in the rural desert location and was discovered lodged under the owner's home by rescuers. She was scared and pregnant and very unsure of her new fosters. Macie had to be trapped in
order to be rescued. Macie learned to trust the rescuers In NM and she had a litter of 7 puppies. Desire is one of them. The others have been adopted. Macie has been with RMPR for 4 months now. She was not trusting in her foster home at first. She still does not like strangers until they are introduced, but once they are, she loves them. She is generous and sweet and very intelligent. She is one of the best mother dogs we as a rescue have encountered in 10 years. She is housebroken, obedient, and learns quickly. When she first came to RMPR she hid under a curio cabinet in the foster home and would use that as her " safe base " now she uses a couch to sleep and survey her surroundings. She is not leash trained but will leash up and she is very social with other dogs. She had to learn to share attention and she is quite adept at learning quickly with gentle positive reinforcement she thrives, but loud noises or voices will frighten her. She is learning what cats are and is not sure about them. She would do well in a home without small children, under 12 years of age. She likes women but is hesitant with loud and large men.

DESIREE is a beautiful puppy of 4 months of age. RMPR received her and her litter mates when she was merely 5 weeks of age. Upon turning 8 weeks the entire litter was spayed. Desiree didn‘t do well with the protocol drugs used and died and was resuscitated. She was then placed in an ER under oxygen. She has visited the vet 3 times since her episode and her recovery is remarkable. She had to learn to walk, run and eat on her own... and she did! She has been with us for 4 months and has learned to interact and socialize with many dogs and loves to play. She loves her mother, Macie who has the ultimate patience to play and interact with Desi. Desiree is affectionate and social but some things come slower for her. She is a beautiful small dog with much
love to give. Due to her circumstances, we will ONLY adopt Desiree with her mother Macie. We at RMPR are looking for a home that understands and loves dogs as they are, and can accept whatever love and happiness they will share. A person that understands it is always about the dog and nothing else. We love Macie and Desi and know in the right household they will thrive. Please NO cats or small children.

Thank you. The adoption fee is 400 for the pair.
animal.name: MACIE & DESIREE

animal.description:
Waverly's mom (Willa) came to our shelter VERY pregnant and delivered six puppies just days after arriving to her foster home.  The babies struggled a lot in their first three months of life- horrible coccidia, major worm infestations, and a case of parvo that nearly took their lives.  Thanks to an amazing team of volunteers who worked around the clock (and a team of veterinary professionals too), all six puppies (and mom) survived. 

Waverly is a pretty girl looking for a forever family. She is 15 weeks old and weighs 20+ pounds.  She is expected to be about 70-80 lbs at adult weight. Her mom is a Rottie/Hound Mix (see photo- Willa) and we don't know a thing about dad.  Based on her size and shape of her head, we're guessing he was a Mastiff or Great Dane mix.

Waverly is spayed; vaccinated for rabies, distemper, and bordetella; and microchipped with a lifetime registration. She is current on flea/tick and prevention too.

Interested in meeting Waverly? Please visit our website www.HalfwayHomeRescue.org and complete an adoption application. Adoption donation $550.

We anticipate a LOT of applications for these puppies.  At this time, we are ONLY accepting applications from CT residents.  Applicants must own their homes and be able to provide proof of ownership.  Applications that do not meet the criteria, will not be considered.

SHELTER STAFF SAYS:  Looking for a good ranch dog who is ready to protect you and your flock? Blizzard is looking for a farm or ranch to call his own. Blizzard is a typical Pyrenees who doesn't care for a lot of human interaction and would prefer to be a hardworking member of the family. Don't let that fool ya though, he does have a playful side and will show his excitement of having you around. Does Blizzard sound like a match for your family? Come on out and meet him today and you will fall in LOVE!

Due to Covid, we now work by appointment only and work on a first come basis.  If you are interested in making an appointment, please call the HCHS at 512-793-5463.  You can see all our available animals at HillCountryHumaneSociety.org.
All our adoptable dogs are treated for fleas, given DHPPV and Bordatella vaccines and are de-wormed.  
When you adopt one of our animals it will be micro chipped and registered at the time of adoption.  Also, if not already altered, you will receive a voucher to get your animal spay/neutered.
While we do our best to determine the breeds of our dogs, the majority are strays, and we have only general appearance, coat type, size, ear type, tail, tongue color and coat color to base breed on.  It is always possible when adopting a puppy that it will change dramatically to look like another breed.

animal.description:
Annie has quite the background story. She was a stray in Tennessee, along with her mate, an American Bulldog mix, and her litter of puppies. A former Second Chance adopter (“K”) who had moved there became aware of Annie because an acquaintance told her Annie’s canine family was frequenting their property and they were looking to get rid of them, with a family member threatening to shoot them. “K” called Second Chance in a panic and asked if we could help them and she offered to drive them up to MN. We said we would help and started to make a plan . Before we could put plans in place, we received another urgent call telling us that the person who had threatened to shoot them had actually shot the male in the stomach and he was laying, bleeding from his wounds. “K” rushed over to the property and asked if she could get him to a Vet and  they said to let him die but “K” wouldn’t give up and with help from a different family member, loaded him into her car, called us to ask for help as she couldn’t afford emergency services, and started driving to an Emergency Clinic. After trying to stabilize him and fully evaluating his condition, the Vet called us and said his injuries were too severe and recommended humane euthanasia; his stomach & intestines were too damaged to successfully repair. “K” then realized she needed to get Annie & puppies off the property ASAP so enlisted the help of a friend and they went over, gathered then up and drove off, then took time off work to drive the stray family up to MN.
 
  Annie is a mixed breed girl. Some have labeled her a Rottweiler X, some a Doberman X, some an American Staffie X but she is smaller than all of the above and really doesn’t look like any of these breeds.  In searching our Breed Books, we just went with the closest resemblance we could find, which turned out to be a Beauceron (French Shepherd), so we are calling her a mini Beauceron.
She is about 3 years old and weighs 50 lbs.  Annie’s foster calls her the sweetest dog ever and the best dog they have ever fostered. Annie is affectionate, loving, mellow, easy-going, and well behaved. She is good with women, men, dogs, cats (ignores them), and kids – she is good with the foster’s 5 yr old daughter, and we were told that when “K” went on walks with Annie in TN,  a tiny little 3 year girl along with her siblings would come running  out to Annie for pets and hugs. Annie is housetrained and has never had an accident in the house although sometimes it takes a bit of walking to get her to go potty.  On walks, Annie needs to wear a harness or a martingale type collar that tightens up when she pulls because her neck is thicker than her head and a regular collar can easily slip off . Annie currently lives with adults and 2 other dogs and her people do not have long work days away from home. She hasn’t needed to be crated. She does, however seem to get somewhat depressed when people are occasionally gone for more than 5 hours and on those occasions she is ecstatic when her people come home. She would love to have a retired person or someone that works from home adopt her.  Her favorite things are cuddles, snuggles, food, & walks. 
Annie has been spayed, and is current on distemper and rabies vaccinations. She tested positive for heartworm disease on intake, and was successfully treated – a follow-up heartworm test on November 11 of 2020 was negative. Her microchip is registered to Second Chance. Annie has a $395 adoption fee. Call 651-771-5662 if you are interested in Annie.

animal.description:
***All applications will be considered before inquiries as we do not currently have the staff to respond to every inquiry submitted. 

Please meet Sangria’s babies!  They are typical puppies!  Playful, bouncy, energetic, curious, always starving, and quite simply adorable. They love attention, playing with toys, and love meeting new people. They are working on crate training and on housebreaking. They understand the concept and if consistent, they will head out the door. If they get busy in the toy basket, it might be too late!  They are young and will need supervision and lots of patience. They try so hard and they love treats!  They are learning how to walk on a leash, but with all puppies, will need continued training, consistency and lots and lots of love.  They play well with other dogs, but they have not been formally cat tested. They are a bit excitable about the kitties, so we have just been able to do fence greetings at this time.  

If these pups spark your interest, Then jump in line and apply!  Our app is on the home page, These puppies are gonna fly!

OUR APPLICATION LINK CAN BE FOUND ON OUR PETFINDER PAGE UNDER THE PIC OF THE DOG. 

ANIMAL INFORMATION:  
Name:   Lager
Breed:  Collie/Lab mix
Gender:  Male
Age:  3 months
Weight: 15 lbs           
Spayed/Neutered: Yes
Vaccines: Current
Heartworm:  Too Young
Microchipped: Yes

FOSTER EVALUATION AND RECOMMENDATION:
Dogs:  Yes, fostering with other dogs of various sizes, genders and breeds
Cats:   Yes. They have met cats, but needs a slow meet and greet since they are puppy excitable. Recommend proper intro. 
Other Small Animals:  Unknown
Children:  Yes, they have met middle age children and have done well. They have not been tested with infants or toddlers. They are excitable and bouncy at times, and could potentially knock a little one down or get under their feet. 


ADOPTION INFORMATION:
We are a foster-based animal rescue and we thank you for your interest in one of our animals. Our fosters and adoption coordinators are the backbone of what we do. Our fosters work tirelessly to integrate our rescue animals into their home, so that we can provide as much information to potential adopters as possible. In addition, our coordinators offer as much information regarding the medical and behavioral and personality characteristics as is known to our organization. Without them, and our extremely generous donors, we would not be able to save as many animals as we do every day. With each adoption, we operate a Pay It Forward program, whenever possible, to help other animals in our rescue and future animals in need. 

If you are interested in one of our animals, please complete an application. The application link can be found on our Petfinder homepage under the picture. You may also find our application on our website at www.petmatchmakerrescue.com under the Adopt page. If they are listed on our website, their adoptions have not been finalized yet. That does not mean that we have not received several applications, already. Please complete an application if you are interested and we will keep you apprised of their current status. We are all volunteers that work full-time jobs, so please be patient with us. We will get back with you as quickly as possible.  

If you are interested in fostering for our organization, please complete an application.  The application link can be found on our Petfinder homepage under the picture.
